r? @alexcrichton

(rust_highfive has picked a reviewer for you, use r? to override)
Nice! I've wondered in the past if we should just start using libbacktrace for everything instead of just symbols/filenames/line numbers, it's got a pretty good track record so far.

Accidentally closed the PR there for a second! Anyway, I've made the changes you suggested - I'm mostly held back by how long it takes to build everything, so I've still been unable to test properly in all configurations.
Thanks! Just one minor nit and r=me after a squashing of the last 6 commits

Er actually, just remembered, there's a test that tests for line numbers and can you be sure that it's enabled on GNU windows now? I believe the test is `src/test/run-pass/backtrace-debuginfo.rs`

@bors: r-
I've enabled the tests, and they seem to be passing.

> https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/28004#issuecomment-135802711.
Hmm, for some reason `pwd` on buildbot outputs a windows-style path. It's supposed to only do that when passing `-W`.

There tend to be somewhat odd inconsistencies between the environment that our buildbots run in from a native MSYS shell. It generally has to do with the order of `PATH` and what programs are in it, but yeah it looks like there's problems with the new configure script for libbacktrace.
I suspect the problem always existed, but libbacktrace was never built on windows before this pr. I could remove the check from configure, but that may cause more breakages down the line.

Hm right, good point. If you need any help getting this working just let me know, but what I've tried in the past is to look at the environment variables set by buildbot and open up a `cmd.exe` shell with similar values, and then try to build. That normally gets at least relatively close to the same build environment modulo versions of things.

I can't test right now as I'm away for the weekend, but buildbot seems to have two versions of mingw on PATH, the normal msys one, and `c:\mingw-w64\x86_64-4.9.1-win32-seh-rt_v3-rev1\mingw64\bin`. What's that about? It would certainly explain why the bots seem to exhibit such different behaviour.

It turns out this is a bug in buildbot, which may or may not have been fixed in newer versions: http://trac.buildbot.net/ticket/456

This page describes a work-around in the event that it hasn't:
http://trac.buildbot.net/wiki/CygwinShellCommands

I think it's also possible to fix by modifying `rt.mk`, although that solution is somewhat hacky.

Which solution is preferred?
We chatted a bit on IRC, but the gist of it is that updating buildbot is quite difficult where modifying `rt.mk` is much easier, so I'd prefer to keep piling the hacks in `rt.mk` for now at least.

Fixing this is currently blocked by the fact that I'm unable to build rustc to stage2 under `i686-pc-windows-gnu`, due to the stage1 rustc segfaulting while compiling stage2 libsyntax. It appears to be an llvm bug, and it's proving to be very difficult to reproduce with debug builds of llvm (rustc seems to hang instead of crashing, or it could just be _very_ slow), and Release+Asserts did not help.

The Release backtrace only showed that it _might_ be happening inside llvm's tail-call elimination pass.

@Diggsey yeah I've seen that happen unfortunately with gcc 5.2.0, although I'm not sure how to downgrade... Last I checked (a few weeks ago I think) it also happened with the HEAD LLVM, and unfortunately I haven't tracked it down much farther than that :(
Ok, I've just disabled the two backtrace tests on 32-bit windows-gnu again, since the problem seems to be unrelated to this PR (#28218).
:umbrella: The latest upstream changes (presumably #28200) made this pull request unmergeable. Please resolve the merge conflicts.

@jonas-schievink Neither of those tests were enabled on windows before this PR, so it's a safe bet that this caused it.

It looks like for some reason libbacktrace is unable to access the dwarf debug info on the executable. Most likely causes are eiither there's no debug info being generated in the first place, or there's some new security restriction on windows 10 that's preventing it.
